1
00:00:04,338 --> 00:00:06,204
We are having a baby.

2
00:00:08,008 --> 00:00:09,203
Morning, Shaun.

3
00:00:09,810 --> 00:00:12,837
- Were you watching me sleep?
- Yes.

4
00:00:13,914 --> 00:00:15,542
We are having a baby.

5
00:00:19,186 --> 00:00:24,420
That baby is making me feel
like I ate three-month-old sushi.

6
00:00:26,827 --> 00:00:29,296
Good morning, berry.

7
00:00:29,363 --> 00:00:31,992
Why are you making
Mommy feel this way?

8
00:00:32,065 --> 00:00:34,728
Are we naming it Berry?

9
00:00:35,402 --> 00:00:38,167
For now, because he's
the size of a blueberry.

10
00:00:38,672 --> 00:00:44,373
I can just picture your face on
a little blueberry-sized baby...

11
00:00:45,546 --> 00:00:47,174
At week seven,

12
00:00:47,247 --> 00:00:49,773
the fetus has developed
webbed hands and feet.

13
00:00:49,850 --> 00:00:52,217
And you have started
to form a mucus plug...

14
00:00:53,186 --> 00:00:54,677
Your breath is
killing me, Shaun.

15
00:00:56,823 --> 00:00:59,292
I brushed my teeth. Twice.

16
00:00:59,359 --> 00:01:01,692
Because I thought
we might have sex.

17
00:01:01,762 --> 00:01:04,823
The mint from the...
The toothpaste is... It's...

18
00:01:06,433 --> 00:01:07,696
Mm-mm.

19
00:01:13,106 --> 00:01:15,905
Stop smirking like
you're picturing me naked.

20
00:01:15,976 --> 00:01:18,036
Don't have to picture
it. Saw it already.

21
00:01:18,111 --> 00:01:20,808
You're running a little late. Did I
keep you up too long last night?

22
00:01:20,881 --> 00:01:23,851
Don't flatter yourself. I'm
not late and it wasn't that long.

23
00:01:25,586 --> 00:01:26,747
What are you doing?

24
00:01:28,422 --> 00:01:29,549
Shielding us from the rain?

25
00:01:29,623 --> 00:01:31,319
What do you think
this is, <i>The Notebook?</i>

26
00:01:31,391 --> 00:01:34,361
It's raining and I
shared my umbrella.

27
00:01:36,396 --> 00:01:38,558
Having sex doesn't
make us a thing.

28
00:01:39,232 --> 00:01:40,757
We need to make
clear boundaries.

29
00:01:40,834 --> 00:01:42,928
I don't need romantic
gestures from you.

30
00:01:43,003 --> 00:01:46,804
I shared my umbrella, I didn't propose.
But I hear your message, loud and clear.

31
00:01:46,873 --> 00:01:48,171
You hate me. I hate you.

32
00:01:48,976 --> 00:01:49,976
See you tonight?

33
00:01:56,283 --> 00:01:57,410
Can I help you?

34
00:01:58,652 --> 00:01:59,711
Hello, Claire.

35
00:01:59,786 --> 00:02:01,448
My name is Miles Browne. I'm...

36
00:02:03,190 --> 00:02:04,190
your father.

37
00:02:08,161 --> 00:02:11,529
- What are you doing here?
- I've owed you a lot of answers

38
00:02:11,598 --> 00:02:14,033
- for a long time, and...
- Go home.

39
00:02:14,101 --> 00:02:15,262
Um... Oh.

40
00:02:15,335 --> 00:02:16,335
I just, uh...

41
00:02:18,939 --> 00:02:21,807
What I... Well, I
wish I was a better...

42
00:02:23,210 --> 00:02:24,210
Um...

43
00:02:25,612 --> 00:02:29,743
I don't want you to... hate...

44
00:02:29,816 --> 00:02:30,816
Can you lift your arms?

45
00:02:32,185 --> 00:02:33,448
Keep them up.

46
00:02:34,221 --> 00:02:36,781
Okay. Repeat after me,
"Don't cry over spilled milk."

47
00:02:37,524 --> 00:02:39,652
Don't... F... Fry...

48
00:02:40,927 --> 00:02:43,567
We need to get you to the hospital.
I think you're having a stroke.

49
00:02:54,975 --> 00:02:57,034
The quickstep is my nemesis.

50
00:02:57,110 --> 00:02:59,477
I lost my footing and
landed on a 90-year-old judge

51
00:02:59,546 --> 00:03:01,572
with very sharp elbows.

52
00:03:01,648 --> 00:03:05,278
And he insisted I come
in even though I'm fine.

53
00:03:05,352 --> 00:03:06,786
Just a little sore.

54
00:03:06,853 --> 00:03:09,687
Yeah, but Maya's "a little sore"
is a normal person's excruciating.

55
00:03:10,757 --> 00:03:12,419
Take the compliment, babe.

56
00:03:14,061 --> 00:03:15,427
You're shivering.

57
00:03:15,495 --> 00:03:19,227
The abdomen is tense and
distended. She's hypotensive.

58
00:03:19,299 --> 00:03:22,565
We need to do an ultrasound to
check for acute abdominal injury.

59
00:03:22,636 --> 00:03:24,127
I'm fine.

60
00:03:25,138 --> 00:03:26,902
When did you start
feeling lightheaded?

61
00:03:28,008 --> 00:03:29,032
About an hour ago.

62
00:03:29,843 --> 00:03:32,244
There is significant pressure
on the abdominal contents.

63
00:03:33,914 --> 00:03:37,078
- What does that mean?
- She has a retroperitoneal bleed.

64
00:03:37,150 --> 00:03:39,483
We need to get you
into surgery right away.

65
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:49,628
Hi, Mr. Browne. I'm
Dr. Allen, this is Dr. Park.

66
00:03:49,696 --> 00:03:51,688
- How are you feeling?
- Much better.

67
00:03:51,765 --> 00:03:53,393
I see where Claire
gets her good looks.

68
00:03:55,469 --> 00:03:59,964
BP looks good. 124 over 83. Have
you had these symptoms before?

69
00:04:00,040 --> 00:04:02,532
Happens sometimes
when I get migraines.

70
00:04:02,609 --> 00:04:04,976
Yeah. Migraines come
when I'm stressed.

71
00:04:05,912 --> 00:04:08,404
Don't cry over spilled milk.

72
00:04:11,551 --> 00:04:14,146
Look. I don't want to take
up too much of your time,

73
00:04:14,221 --> 00:04:17,316
but is it possible we can go
somewhere quiet and talk?

74
00:04:17,390 --> 00:04:19,689
Maybe we could grab
a coffee or dessert.

75
00:04:19,760 --> 00:04:22,662
You know, you used to
love Rocky Road ice cream.

76
00:04:22,729 --> 00:04:24,095
Is that still your favorite?

77
00:04:24,164 --> 00:04:26,429
You just had a major
neurological event.

78
00:04:26,500 --> 00:04:29,265
We need to run some CT
scans to identify the cause.

79
00:04:32,205 --> 00:04:33,673
Found the bleeder. Clamp.

80
00:04:33,740 --> 00:04:36,801
We need to open up the
retroperitoneal space and pack.

81
00:04:36,877 --> 00:04:37,970
BP's still dropping.

82
00:04:38,044 --> 00:04:41,105
It's not clotting. She have any history
of hemophilia or bleeding disorder?

83
00:04:41,181 --> 00:04:43,980
- No.
- Push FFP, TXA, and fibrinogen.

84
00:04:44,050 --> 00:04:46,281
Pack more lap pads and
evacuate the hematoma.

85
00:04:53,593 --> 00:04:55,619
Pressure's rising.

86
00:05:01,968 --> 00:05:05,871
This young lady almost died
from a collision with an elbow.

87
00:05:05,939 --> 00:05:07,874
There must be something
else going on here.

88
00:05:07,941 --> 00:05:09,341
Find out what it is.

89
00:05:23,957 --> 00:05:26,825
We'll start by scanning your
abdomen. I'll help you up on the bed.

90
00:05:29,196 --> 00:05:30,196
You were right.

91
00:05:30,964 --> 00:05:32,830
<i>It wasn't a migraine.</i>

92
00:05:36,603 --> 00:05:38,071
I have terminal cancer.

93
00:05:47,514 --> 00:05:50,211
His oncologist started him
on chemo, it shrunk the tumor,

94
00:05:50,283 --> 00:05:51,911
but Miles didn't finish it.

95
00:05:51,985 --> 00:05:54,887
The location of the metastases
still likely leaves it inoperable.

96
00:05:54,955 --> 00:05:58,653
I don't know. If we use transcatheter
hepatic artery chemoembolization,

97
00:05:58,725 --> 00:06:01,320
we might be able to attack
the tumor and spare his liver.

98
00:06:03,296 --> 00:06:05,390
Claire, what do you think?

99
00:06:08,368 --> 00:06:10,337
It's the patient's decision.

100
00:06:10,403 --> 00:06:12,372
You should take it to him.

101
00:06:12,439 --> 00:06:13,463
Let him decide.

102
00:06:18,945 --> 00:06:21,642
You have abnormally
large platelets.

103
00:06:22,415 --> 00:06:24,941
It's a rare condition called
Bernard-Soulier syndrome,

104
00:06:25,018 --> 00:06:27,180
which makes it difficult
for your blood to clot.

105
00:06:27,254 --> 00:06:29,018
It's why you almost
bled out during surgery.

106
00:06:29,089 --> 00:06:31,115
Is it treatable?
Will she be okay?

107
00:06:31,191 --> 00:06:33,183
There's no cure,
but it is manageable.

108
00:06:33,260 --> 00:06:37,698
Keep an eye out for pain or bruising or
any other symptoms that don't go away.

109
00:06:37,764 --> 00:06:39,858
That could be a sign
of a larger problem.

110
00:06:39,933 --> 00:06:42,767
- It's just a pulled muscle.
- You don't know that.

111
00:06:44,304 --> 00:06:47,274
My left leg has been
bothering me for a few weeks.

112
00:06:47,340 --> 00:06:48,340
Months.

113
00:06:50,944 --> 00:06:53,072
I'm not overreacting.

114
00:06:57,450 --> 00:06:59,817
We'll need to run CTs
of your hip and femur

115
00:06:59,886 --> 00:07:02,355
to rule out osteoarthritis
or an occult fracture.

116
00:07:08,061 --> 00:07:10,394
- How does that feel?
- Weird.

117
00:07:15,902 --> 00:07:17,962
- Better?
- Sure.

118
00:07:18,038 --> 00:07:19,370
Why do I need this?

119
00:07:19,439 --> 00:07:23,069
Back pain is a common symptom
of pregnancy. It's preventative.

120
00:07:23,977 --> 00:07:27,744
You should take these twice a day,
with food or milk. Preferably food.

121
00:07:27,814 --> 00:07:29,407
I already have
prenatal vitamins.

122
00:07:29,482 --> 00:07:33,249
You have the chewable gummy
kind. Tablets are better for the fetus.

123
00:07:33,320 --> 00:07:34,948
Okay, please stop
calling it a fetus.

124
00:07:35,021 --> 00:07:38,287
- It is a fetus.
- It's our baby.

125
00:07:39,693 --> 00:07:42,322
Okay, I don't need you
to do any of this, Shaun.

126
00:07:45,131 --> 00:07:46,997
What do you need me to do?

127
00:07:47,067 --> 00:07:50,936
Just... be the
dad, not the doctor.

128
00:07:57,444 --> 00:07:59,970
Do you think I'm going
to drink this? What's in it?

129
00:08:00,046 --> 00:08:02,481
Urine? Saliva? A tropical fish?

130
00:08:02,549 --> 00:08:03,847
Coffee.

131
00:08:04,851 --> 00:08:07,150
Dr. Park, I need to talk
to you about our patient.

132
00:08:07,220 --> 00:08:09,712
Let's do an additional
split-thickness skin graft.

133
00:08:09,789 --> 00:08:11,917
That's a long,
complicated procedure.

134
00:08:11,992 --> 00:08:14,518
If you're going to scrub
in, you'll need the caffeine.

135
00:08:14,594 --> 00:08:16,756
I hear you've been keeping
some pretty late nights.

136
00:08:19,432 --> 00:08:22,402
Too much caffeine before
surgery leads to unsteady hands.

137
00:08:22,469 --> 00:08:25,303
I can assure you I am well
rested. I don't need the coffee.

138
00:08:38,985 --> 00:08:40,783
Your father refused surgery.

139
00:08:44,057 --> 00:08:46,754
His slurred speech was
a side effect of chemo.

140
00:08:46,826 --> 00:08:50,160
Treatment almost took him
out. He doesn't want to try again.

141
00:08:51,898 --> 00:08:53,127
Thanks for letting me know.

142
00:09:01,641 --> 00:09:03,906
I know a lot of girls who
didn't have their fathers.

143
00:09:04,677 --> 00:09:07,010
But yours did
something theirs didn't...

144
00:09:08,214 --> 00:09:09,409
he came back.

145
00:09:10,083 --> 00:09:11,915
He came back to
absolve himself of guilt.

146
00:09:12,786 --> 00:09:15,915
That's a gift I'm not giving
him. That's his burden to carry.

147
00:09:15,989 --> 00:09:18,390
Forgiveness isn't for
the one you're forgiving.

148
00:09:19,692 --> 00:09:21,024
It's for you.

149
00:09:25,331 --> 00:09:28,096
It's Miles. His
liver's bleeding.

150
00:09:31,104 --> 00:09:32,367
Go.

151
00:09:44,717 --> 00:09:46,447
They seem like a
very nice couple.

152
00:09:47,187 --> 00:09:49,088
Very... connected.

153
00:09:51,624 --> 00:09:53,388
I wish I knew
how to be like that.

154
00:09:55,428 --> 00:09:56,919
They're not a couple.

155
00:09:58,298 --> 00:09:59,766
Leo's gay.

156
00:10:00,867 --> 00:10:03,564
Can gay people really
detect other gay people?

157
00:10:04,270 --> 00:10:06,637
You can if you check
out their Instagram.

158
00:10:08,374 --> 00:10:09,637
Dr. Murphy...

159
00:10:10,577 --> 00:10:14,070
I don't think she has arthritis,
but I don't know what this is.

160
00:10:17,050 --> 00:10:20,987
Her disorder caused blood-filled
pseudotumors in her leg.

161
00:10:22,388 --> 00:10:24,448
The blood ate away her bone.

162
00:10:29,729 --> 00:10:33,393
Your liver was bleeding because
your tumor exceeded its blood supply.

163
00:10:34,434 --> 00:10:36,869
It puts you at risk for
serious complications...

164
00:10:37,570 --> 00:10:39,129
even a fatal one.

165
00:10:40,073 --> 00:10:42,508
Please reconsider the surgery.

166
00:10:42,575 --> 00:10:44,407
Yeah, I'm not afraid of dying.

167
00:10:46,012 --> 00:10:48,675
Where's my daughter? Why isn't
she here telling me any of this?

168
00:10:59,459 --> 00:11:01,257
I think it's time
for me to go home.

169
00:11:02,962 --> 00:11:05,397
What about 3D
printed scaffolding?

170
00:11:05,465 --> 00:11:08,060
We could recreate the shape
of the bone, graft new stem cells,

171
00:11:08,134 --> 00:11:10,899
and allograft onto it to
generate new growth.

172
00:11:10,970 --> 00:11:14,031
Her underlying disorder
would eat away the new bone.

173
00:11:14,107 --> 00:11:17,202
Everything I do upsets Lea
and makes her mad at me.

174
00:11:19,479 --> 00:11:21,744
Oh, that's what I'm
doing here, I'm guessing?

175
00:11:21,814 --> 00:11:26,013
Mm-hm. Yes. You're both here
because I have two questions.

176
00:11:26,653 --> 00:11:28,781
When I tell my patient her
femur bone is destroyed,

177
00:11:28,855 --> 00:11:32,417
she is going to ask if I can save her
leg and I don't have an answer to that.

178
00:11:32,492 --> 00:11:34,961
Lea and I are in love.
We're going to have a baby.

179
00:11:35,028 --> 00:11:37,088
We should feel
very happy right now,

180
00:11:37,163 --> 00:11:41,225
but I feel like I'm living with a stranger
who doesn't want me to breathe on them.

181
00:11:42,335 --> 00:11:45,066
We could do an expandable
Osseo integrated limb replacement.

182
00:11:45,138 --> 00:11:46,698
- Too risky.
- Too many surgeries, yeah.

183
00:11:48,441 --> 00:11:51,741
Well, you're going to have
a kid, Shaun, and you...

184
00:11:51,811 --> 00:11:53,973
You can't expect
everything to be the same.

185
00:11:54,047 --> 00:11:55,879
Lea's going through
a whole lot of changes.

186
00:11:55,949 --> 00:11:56,949
You both are.

187
00:11:57,550 --> 00:12:00,987
- No. I'm the same.
- Well, maybe that's the problem, Shaun.

188
00:12:01,054 --> 00:12:04,149
You're in a relationship
with three people now.

189
00:12:04,724 --> 00:12:06,522
You're going to have
to make adjustments.

190
00:12:06,593 --> 00:12:07,593
Both of you.

191
00:12:12,565 --> 00:12:13,565
Okay.

192
00:12:14,734 --> 00:12:16,760
We could use
high-density polyethylene

193
00:12:16,836 --> 00:12:19,237
on the distal femoral segment
to anchor it to the tendons.

194
00:12:20,106 --> 00:12:21,472
I don't like adjusting.

195
00:12:30,516 --> 00:12:31,575
You wanted to see me.

196
00:12:34,988 --> 00:12:38,049
If we discharge
him, he's going to die.

197
00:12:40,927 --> 00:12:46,059
I don't expect you would feel
anything but contempt for Miles.

198
00:12:46,132 --> 00:12:49,034
He was supposed to take
care of you and he didn't.

199
00:12:50,370 --> 00:12:54,102
And now I'm asking you to do
for him what he never did for you.

200
00:12:54,173 --> 00:12:56,699
Oh, he did take care
of me. He just quit.

201
00:12:58,911 --> 00:13:00,812
He used to pick me up
every day after school.

202
00:13:04,917 --> 00:13:06,408
And then one day he just...

203
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:08,579
stopped showing up.

204
00:13:10,823 --> 00:13:13,224
And for years after,
I would come home,

205
00:13:13,926 --> 00:13:15,588
I'd make sure the
curtains were open...

206
00:13:16,596 --> 00:13:17,757
and I'd wait.

207
00:13:18,898 --> 00:13:20,696
If a car slowed down
in front of the house,

208
00:13:20,767 --> 00:13:23,760
I'd imagine it was him coming
to grab me up and rescue me.

209
00:13:23,836 --> 00:13:26,499
And I thought if I wanted
it enough, he'd come back.

210
00:13:26,572 --> 00:13:29,667
So I just had to want
it more, you know?

211
00:13:33,313 --> 00:13:35,680
And finally, I gave up. I
stopped looking out the window.

212
00:13:40,353 --> 00:13:43,551
I grieved and buried my father
a long time ago, and I'm just...

213
00:13:43,623 --> 00:13:49,187
I'm not interested in getting to know
him just to grieve him all over again.

214
00:13:53,700 --> 00:13:56,932
But he's still your father.
And you're still you.

215
00:14:00,640 --> 00:14:03,075
Someday you'll hate yourself
if you turn your back on him.

216
00:14:08,748 --> 00:14:12,617
We would secure the titanium
prosthetic to the hip socket and tibia

217
00:14:12,685 --> 00:14:15,484
using cement augmentation
for stability and support.

218
00:14:15,555 --> 00:14:18,457
You would have full
flexibility and range of motion.

219
00:14:18,524 --> 00:14:21,892
And with physical therapy, you
should be able to dance again.

220
00:14:22,628 --> 00:14:23,823
If you survive the surgery.

221
00:14:25,732 --> 00:14:27,667
- I could die?
- Yes.

222
00:14:27,734 --> 00:14:30,829
There is a 10 to 15 percent
chance. Approximately.

223
00:14:30,903 --> 00:14:33,600
Femur replacement is a
very complicated procedure

224
00:14:33,673 --> 00:14:36,541
made even riskier by
your underlying condition.

225
00:14:36,609 --> 00:14:38,942
The safest route is to amputate.

226
00:14:39,011 --> 00:14:42,709
Very little chance of major
complication during surgery.

227
00:14:42,782 --> 00:14:45,513
And there have been great
advancements in prosthetics.

228
00:14:46,018 --> 00:14:47,680
My dance career would be over.

229
00:14:49,155 --> 00:14:51,681
Most likely. But you
would still have your life.

230
00:14:53,025 --> 00:14:54,550
My life is dance.

231
00:14:57,730 --> 00:14:59,392
Do whatever it
takes to save the leg.

232
00:14:59,465 --> 00:15:03,129
Oh, Maya. It's too big a risk.

233
00:15:03,770 --> 00:15:05,329
But you know what
this means to me.

234
00:15:08,641 --> 00:15:11,668
But if there's a chance
I could die tomorrow,

235
00:15:13,146 --> 00:15:15,377
there's something
I have to do first.

236
00:15:15,448 --> 00:15:17,576
<i>♪ I played my cards wrong ♪</i>

237
00:15:17,650 --> 00:15:20,620
<i>♪ Oh, just a little bit wrong ♪</i>

238
00:15:20,686 --> 00:15:26,523
<i>♪ Baby I apologize for it ♪</i>

239
00:15:26,592 --> 00:15:31,929
<i>♪ I could fall, or I could
fly Here in your aeroplane ♪</i>

240
00:15:31,998 --> 00:15:37,198
<i>♪ And I could live, I could die
